  "prompt": "Why don't US representatives run for president?",
  "response": "U.S. representatives can and do run for president, but there are several reasons why it may not be as common as candidates from other backgrounds:\n\n1. **Political Landscape**: Many presidential candidates come from the Senate or governorships, which are perceived as more significant launching pads for a presidential bid. Senators and governors often have broader recognition and deeper networks.\n\n2. **Visibility and Experience**: Senators typically have a longer tenure and national recognition than representatives, who serve in the House for shorter two-year terms. This can make them more appealing to voters looking for experience at the national level.\n\n3. **Time and Commitments**: The House of Representatives has a busy schedule and representatives must balance their congressional duties with campaigning. The demands of campaigning can be difficult to manage alongside serving their constituents.\n\n4. **Perception of the House**: The House of Representatives is often seen as a more partisan institution, so representatives may be less likely to be viewed as viable candidates by a broader electorate.\n\n5. **Strategic Calculations**: Politicians may choose to wait and build their credentials before running for president. Some representatives might consider serving longer in Congress or seeking a higher-profile role first.\n\nDespite these factors, there have been several successful presidential candidates from the House of Representatives, such as James A. Garfield, John F. Kennedy, and more recently, candidates like Newt Gingrich, who ran in the primaries but did not win the nomination.",
